## ðŸ”¹ What is Recursion?

Recursion is a programming technique where a function
calls itself to solve a problem by breaking it into
smaller sub-problems.

Every recursive function must have:
- **Base Case** â€“ stops recursion
- **Recursive Case** â€“ function calls itself

---

## ðŸ“š Types of Recursion Covered

### 1ï¸âƒ£ Direct Recursion
A function calls itself directly.

**Example:** Factorial  
ðŸ“Œ Used in: factorial, sum, power

---

### 2ï¸âƒ£ Indirect Recursion
A function calls another function which then calls the first function.

ðŸ“Œ Used in: mutually dependent logic

---

### 3ï¸âƒ£ Tail Recursion
Recursive call is the **last statement** in the function.

ðŸ“Œ Faster & memory efficient  
âš ï¸ C++ may optimize it

---

### 4ï¸âƒ£ Non-Tail (Head) Recursion
Some work is done **after** the recursive call.

ðŸ“Œ Output depends on return path

---

### 5ï¸âƒ£ Linear Recursion
Only **one recursive call** per function call.

ðŸ“Œ Time Complexity: **O(n)**

---

### 6ï¸âƒ£ Binary Recursion
Function makes **two recursive calls**.

ðŸ“Œ Example: Fibonacci  
ðŸ“Œ Time Complexity: **O(2â¿)**

---

### 7ï¸âƒ£ Multiple (Tree) Recursion
More than **two recursive calls**.

ðŸ“Œ Used in: tree problems, DP

---

### 8ï¸âƒ£ Nested Recursion
A recursive call inside another recursive call.

ðŸ“Œ Rare but asked in exams

---

### 9ï¸âƒ£ Mutual Recursion
Two or more functions call each other.

ðŸ“Œ Used in: odd-even checks

---

### ðŸ”Ÿ Tree Recursion
Each call generates multiple child calls.

ðŸ“Œ Used in: backtracking, tree traversal

---

## ðŸ“Š Recursion Types Summary

| Type | Recursive Calls | Example |
|-----|-----------------|---------|
| Direct | 1 | Factorial |
| Indirect | â‰¥2 | A â†’ B â†’ A |
| Tail | 1 (last) | Optimized factorial |
